  <question type="stack">
    <name>
      <text>7.3.3.2 Evaluate a 4x4 determinant</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<h4 class="HELM_example">Example</h4>
<p>This exercise is in five parts. Consider the determinant \[\Delta = \det{@matrixa@}\]</p>

<ol class="HELM_parts">

<li>
<p>Use property 2 to find another matrix whose determinant is equal to \(\Delta\):</p> 	
<div>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</div><div><br></div>
</li>

<li>
<p>Now expand along the top row to express \(\Delta\) as the difference of two products, each of a number and a \(3\times 3\) determinant:
</p><div>\(\Delta=\) [[input:ans21]] [[validation:ans21]]\(\times\det\)[[input:ans22]] [[validation:ans22]] \(-\) [[input:ans23]] [[validation:ans23]] \(\times\det\) [[input:ans24]] [[validation:ans24]] [[feedback:prt2]]<p></p>
</div></li>

<li>
<p>Use property 4 to evaluate the first \(3\times3\) determinant: [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]
</p></li>

<li>
<p>Use property 4 to evaluate the second \(3\times3\) determinant: [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]
</p></li>

<li>
<p>Deduce the value of \(\Delta\): [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]] [[feedback:prt5]]
</p></li>

</ol>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text>Property 2 states that the determinant of a matrix is equal to the determinant of its transpose. So the other matrix is just the transpose of the matrix in the question:
\[{@AA@}^{T} = {@AAT@}\]

Expanding along the top row is easiest, because of the two zeros in the row. The formula for the determinant in terms of cofactors tells us:
\[\det{@AA@} = ({@ta21@}){@ta22@}-({@ta23@}){@ta24@}\]
Note the minus sign, which comes from the \(4\times4\) pattern of signs.

In the second of the two \(3\times3\) determinants, the second row is double the first row. Hence the determinant is zero, by Property 4.

In the first of the two \(3\times3\) determinants, the third column is \({@cc/bb@}\) times the second column. Hence this determinant is also zero.

Therefore \(\Delta=0\).</text>
    </generalfeedback>
